    Merge pull request #1147 from protegeproject/fix-broken-macos-file-saving-dialog
    
    Fallback to OS-independent file-saving dialog on macOS

commit 86f07f45da3dce14133b0e978cb42282d86d8853
Author: Damien Goutte-Gattat <dpg44@cam.ac.uk>
Date:   Fri May 5 14:46:55 2023 +0100

    Fallback to OS-independent file-saving dialog on macOS.
    
    On macOS, if we don't get a File from the macOS-specific
    MacUIUtil#saveFile() method, assume this is due to a failure of that
    method (or of the underlying JRE) to even show the native file-choosing
    dialog (as was shown to happen, #1106), and fallback to the
    OS-independent method.
    
    This allow users affected by the "never-showing-native-dialog" bug to
    still save their files, at the price of asking users not affected by
    that same bug to click "cancel" on two consecutive dialogs if they do
    want to cancel the save operation at the file-choosing step.

9	1	protege-editor-core/src/main/java/org/protege/editor/core/ui/util/UIUtil.java

commit fb93698e883c80e5e192186d4cc472770575e55f
Merge: 91b9cdf8 2b05ef27
Author: Damien Goutte-Gattat <dpg44@cam.ac.uk>
Date:   Thu Feb 16 09:52:17 2023 +0000

    Merge pull request #1104 from protegeproject/dont-override-user-extension
    
    Do not override user-provided extension.

commit 2b05ef27b2fc566fab320822198be26b8067f376
Author: Damien Goutte-Gattat <dpg44@cam.ac.uk>
Date:   Wed Feb 15 15:25:38 2023 +0000

    Do not override user-provided extension.
    
    When saving a file under a user-provided name, we check the name for any
    extension. If there is no extension or if the extension is not one of
    the allowed extensions for the chosen file format, we forcibly append an
    allowed extension to the filename.
    
    This commit updates this behaviour to append an extension only in the
    case where there is no extension. If the user-provided filename already
    has an extension, we keep it as it is even if we don't recognize the
    extension.
    
    closes #1087.

0	3	protege-editor-owl/src/main/java/org/protege/editor/owl/OWLEditorKit.java

commit 5e57643d2986653f91084bdf5bf2342b1145af93
Merge: a30db481 36eebf1d
Author: Damien Goutte-Gattat <dpg44@cam.ac.uk>

    Do not allow sub-string matching when recognizing OBO IDs.

commit 36eebf1ded301a309f76c89e02df65c55ee691ce
Author: Damien Goutte-Gattat <dpg44@cam.ac.uk>
Date:   Wed Feb 8 19:06:57 2023 +0000

    Do not allow sub-string matching when recognizing OBO IDs.
    
    The OboUtilities.isOboId() method in org.protege.editor.owl.model.util
    is currently using the Pattern.find() method to check whether its
    argument is an OBO ID.
    
    This is inappropriate as the Pattern.find() method looks for a
    subsequence within the string, instead of attempting to match the full
    string. As a result, a bogus OBO ID such as "MONDO:0018299-obsoleted"
    will be incorrectly identified as a *valid* OBO ID because the
    Pattern.find() method will simply stop matching at the first character
    that does not fit the pattern (the '-'), but will still report that it
    has find a match.
    
    Here, we need to check that the entire string matches the OBO ID
    pattern, which is why this commit replaces the use of Pattern.find() by
    Pattern.match(), which does precisely that.
    
    This is also what the getOboLibraryIriFromOboId method, in the same
    class, is doing. For consistency, isOboId should do the same, so that
    when isOboId returns true, the calling code can then invoke
    getOboLibraryIriFromOboId on the same string and be confident that the
    call would not throw a "Invalid OBO Id" RuntimeException.

1	1	protege-editor-owl/src/main/java/org/protege/editor/owl/model/util/OboUtilities.java

commit a30db481cf56830a9523d681d097d3d999b013e4
Author: Damien Goutte-Gattat <dpg44@cam.ac.uk>
Date:   Wed Jan 18 17:15:30 2023 +0000

    Update the launchers again.
    
    The binary launcher had a 100-characters limit for the length of lines
    in the jvm.conf file. If people need to define OWL API properties in the
    `org.semanticweb.owlapi.model.parameters.ConfigurationOptions`
    namespace, this might be too short.
    
    The new launchers have a 512-characters limit.

-	-	protege-desktop/src/main/env/linux/protege
-	-	protege-desktop/src/main/env/os-x/MacOS/protege
-	-	protege-desktop/src/main/env/win/Protege.exe

commit db7be86f997116e71318f67cd165b615a963b3e0
Author: Damien Goutte-Gattat <dpg44@cam.ac.uk>
Date:   Wed Jan 18 17:08:29 2023 +0000

    Ban the Rio TriX parser.
    
    The TriX parser can return an empty ontology while reporting that it
    successfully loaded an ontology that is _not_ in the TriX format. This
    has the effect of masking any parsing error reported by other parsers,
    while parsing an incorrectly formatted ontology.
    
    The TriX parser is already banned in OWL API >= 5 but still used by
    default in OWL API 4, so we forcefully ban it in Protege.
    
    close #1096

8	0	protege-editor-owl/src/main/java/org/protege/editor/owl/model/io/OntologyLoader.java

Date:   Fri Jan 6 21:58:12 2023 +0000

    Allow JRE selection in the run.sh launcher.
    
    Update the run.sh script (used as fallback in the GNU/Linux version, and
    as generic Unix launcher in the platform-independent version) to use the
    same JRE detection logic as already used in the binary launcher. That
    is, we use successively `java_home` if defined in the configuration
    file, then `PROTEGE_JAVA_HOME` from the environment, then `JAVA_HOME`
    (only if no bundled JRE is available), then finally the bundled JRE.

commit dce2527b0c2b6d1c250c9bb99f9b50c0b3ad59d6
Author: Damien Goutte-Gattat <dpg44@cam.ac.uk>
Date:   Fri Dec 9 15:33:04 2022 +0000

    Update the run.sh script to allow using a JVM configuration file.
    
    For the Linux-specific and the platform-independent package (which both
    relies on a run.sh script to start Protégé), update the run.sh script so
    that it detects a conf/jvm.conf (either in $HOME/.protege or in the
    package itself) and applies Java options found in that file.
    
    The configuratin file is expected to contain 'key=value' lines. Accepted
    keys are:
    
    * max_heap_size (java's -Xmx option)
    * min_heap_size (java's -Xms option)
    * stack_size (java's -Xss option)
    * append (allow passing an arbitrary java option)

commit 93f913574e32e6326fde3f2ba00f1a198cecb21b
Author: Damien Goutte-Gattat <dpg44@cam.ac.uk>
Date:   Thu Nov 17 13:30:40 2022 +0000

    Add arm64 support to the OS X package.
    
    This patch allows to create a OS X package that will run natively on
    both Intel macs and Apple Silicon macs -- provided the os-x JRE package
    we get from https://github.com/protegeproject/mvn-repo is a "universal"
    JRE with support for both architectures.
    
    The original launcher is replaced with a new launcher that is itself a
    universal binary with dual x86-64/arm64 support. The only purpose of
    that launcher is to ensure that the correct architecture is selected at
    startup, something that a script cannot do. The launcher delegates the
    task of actually starting Protégé to the `run.sh` script, where all the
    parameters needed for the Java virtual machine are set.

commit 90ba438b95421bf81d1ff4b102c5b161e3bfb515
Author: Damien Goutte-Gattat <dpg44@cam.ac.uk>
Date:   Tue Oct 11 19:23:18 2022 +0100

    Prevent IndexOutOfBoundsException when highlighting OWL entities
    
    When the class expression editor is trying to find OWL entities that
    match the current text, an IndexOutOfBoundsException can be thrown if
    the user starts by typing a single quote, because at that moment the
    text both starts and ends with a quote, so we try to strip the enclosing
    quotes and end up slicing the string between positions 1 (after the
    "first" quote") and 0 (before the "last" quote).
    
    We prevent the exception by checking that the text is more than one
    character long, in addition to checking whether it starts and ends with
    a quote.

1	1	protege-editor-owl/src/main/java/org/protege/editor/owl/model/find/OWLEntityFinderImpl.java

commit bd8e8dbbf44800feb7533f0995814532601cb2e5
Author: Damien Goutte-Gattat <dpg44@cam.ac.uk>
Date:   Tue Oct 11 19:11:20 2022 +0100

    Restore TAB-triggered completion.
    
    Auto-completion of OWL entities in various fields used to be triggered
    by either the TAB key alone or the CTRL+SPACE combination, until the TAB
    trigger was removed in 4ee78d2.
    
    This patch restores the TAB trigger.

    `.nt` as preferred extension for N-Triples

commit 565e4b1b0abbc467a415b08190d3dffc008f5cf2
Author: Jan Martin Keil <jan-martin.keil@uni-jena.de>
Date:   Mon Jul 26 22:38:45 2021 +0200

    `.nt` as preferred extension for N-Triples
    
    `.nt` should be the preferred [extension of N-Triples](https://www.w3.org/TR/n-triples/#h2_sec-mediaReg-n-triples). `.n3` is the [extension for Notation3](https://www.w3.org/TeamSubmission/n3/). `.n3` is kept as second choice, as it might in practice be used by mistake for N-Triple files.

commit c67cf3e6f1cc06b86a5ab4fd7a28704b94da8686
Author: Nizal <alshammry-nazal@hotmail.com>
Date:   Mon Apr 29 17:51:38 2019 +0100

    requested changes are made on RandomProlong
    
    Changes are as follow:
    1. Remove RandomProlong constructor because it does the same code as in the getNextID method which is irrelevant.
    2. Remove the e.printStackTrace() and use a logger (slf4j) to log exceptions.
    3. Remove the checkpoint() and revert() methods because they do nothing.
    4. Explain why using the getRawID method, because we implement the AbstractIDGenerator interface and we had to implement all of its methods.
    5. Finally, remove the replace("-", "_") statement that was in the code and keep the id generated with dashes in between. The reason for replacing the dashes with underscores in the first place, because I noticed in the UniqueIdGenerator class they used underscores and I thought this preferable in protege.

commit 8bab8b9ce270bc7c73379ddef12eae288dcec04b
Author: Yevgeny Kazakov <yevgeny.kazakov@uni-ulm.de>
Date:   Fri Nov 10 23:02:16 2017 +0100

    Simplify LogViewImpl
    
    1. log is displayed in JTextPane not in JList
    advantages:
    - no custom code for rendering
    - rendering is much fast (previously the whole JList layout was
    re-calculated every time a message is appended)
    - (parts of) messages are now easy to copy / paste
    
    2. Use the native logback PatternLayout to format messages based on a
    format string
    - it is more flexible and easy to configure

commit 54c6629b2880ded1b5f22392994ca2fa5bc0c7eb
Author: Yevgeny Kazakov <yevgeny.kazakov@uni-ulm.de>
Date:   Fri Oct 27 14:25:47 2017 +0200

    Manage recursive calls of OWLCellRenderer
    
    Fix #502.
    
    An OWLCellRenderer object can be used recursively: when rendering a
    cell, its bounds are calculated, which can trigger re-computation of a
    layout, which calls the renderer again. To avoid an infinite recursion,
    a boolean flag was used, thus there can be at most recursion of depth 2.
    But after a recursive call, the variables of the renderer reset and not
    restored. This can result in visual artifacts, i.e., wrong cell
    dimensions in the layout (see #502). This issue is addressed by:
    
    - saving / restoring the OWLCellRenderer variables before / after the
    recursive call
    
    - locking / unlocking OWLCellRenderer to prevent unintended recursive
    calls (when its values are not saved and restored)

171	72	protege-editor-owl/src/main/java/org/protege/editor/owl/ui/renderer/OWLCellRenderer.java

Author: Matthew Horridge <matthew.horridge@stanford.edu>

    - Implemented a faster specialised renderer for the class hierarchy.
    - Cache deprecated entity information.

    is that those that do can actually just deal with the non-collapsing
    presentation.

commit 1c70ca9d7847d69533a52b74b3955b2263dc87eb
Author: Yevgeny Kazakov <yevgeny.kazakov@uni-ulm.de>
Date:   Thu May 18 18:52:08 2017 +0200

    Improve management of embedded dependencies
    
    Embedded dependencies are now specified with the "provided" scope.
    They are also unpacked in the resulting jar instead of being embedded
    (jar in jar).
    
    For example, all classes of mdock are available dirctly from
    protege-editor-core, and if someone uses protege-editor-core in maven,
    the dependency on madock will not be pulled from maven central.
    
    This should help eliminating duplicate classes on the classpath.
    
    Address #611 since now protege-editor-core is provided as a normal
    dependency of protege-editor-owl. Previously it was with the scope
    "provided" which means that it was excluded from transitive
    dependencies.
    
    As before, the scope "provided" scope is used to distinguish embedded
    dependencies from the remaining dependencies when creating bundles

10	12	pom.xml
0	1	protege-common/pom.xml
4	2	protege-editor-core/pom.xml
2	4	protege-editor-owl/pom.xml

commit e2fb0782b4466503af9b97ef4dabd480f242c634
Author: Alexander Stupnikov <saarus72@gmail.com>
Date:   Sun Apr 16 03:04:33 2017 +0200

    Add explanation preferences and its extension point
    
    This adds a new tab "Explanations" in Preferences, in which explanation
    preferences will be shown using a new extension point
    explanationpreferences.
    Each (explanation) plugin can provide an extension to this extension
    point, in which case the preferences of this plugin will be shown as a
    tab in the Explanations tab.
    Otherwise, to provide preferences the plugin would need to extend the
    preferences extension point, which would make the general preference
    menu too crowded. In this way, explanation preferences reflect the logic
    of explanation plugins.

commit e4adbd81a92172dbc26bd8a05f5ea4ae64d9c7d4
Merge: eb64b6ca 0e6d9aea
Author: Matthew Horridge <matthew.horridge@stanford.edu>
Date:   Fri Feb 3 10:47:41 2017 -0800

    Merge pull request #614 from ykazakov/master
    
    Fix delayed progress dialog due to the fix for #574

commit 0e6d9aea36ac7cadd00773a94208107e17f3c6dd
Author: Yevgeny Kazakov <yevgeny.kazakov@uni-ulm.de>
Date:   Fri Feb 3 10:30:21 2017 +0100

    Fix delayed progress dialog due to the fix for #574
    
    Because loading / saving / reloading blocks the event dispatch thread,
    SwingUtilities.invokeLater that were used to show and hide
    the progress dialog, were executed *after* these operations finish.
    
    Now revert the changes to execute dlg.setVisible(true) immediately
    after the main task has been submitted. Since it is executed on
    event dispatch thread, dialog will be shown immediately.
    The dialog will not be hidden before it is shown since
    dlg.setVisible(false) *always* uses SwingUtilities.invokeLater.

commit 5ff29e48fe9f736bec489abd152042aa942e21c9
Merge: e5f3f637 0c94a660
Author: Matthew Horridge <matthew.horridge@stanford.edu>
Date:   Thu Feb 2 11:15:49 2017 -0800

    Merge pull request #604 from ykazakov/master
    
    Improve fix for #574

commit 0c94a6605629088cac75b0ec2b71f5f8f6a6ae1a
Author: Yevgeny Kazakov <yevgeny.kazakov@uni-ulm.de>
Date:   Wed Jan 18 14:37:30 2017 +0100

    Improve fix for #574
    
    - The problem with stuck progress dialog was likely caused by
      the openjdk bug https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-5109571
      using JDialog.dispose() instead of JDialog.setVisible(false)
      seems to avoid this bug
    
    - ProgressDialog: dlg.setVisible(false) is no longer necessary since
    dlg.displose() takes care about hiding the dialog
    
    - ProgressDialog.setVisible() always uses SwingUtilities.invokeLater()
    to ensure that if setVisible(false) is called after setVisible(true)
    then the dialog is shown before it is disposed
    (this may be not true if one is called on EDT and the other is not)
    
    - ensure that ProgressDialog.setVisible(false) is called after
      ProgressDialog.setVisible(true); this was not the case, e.g.,
      in OntologySaver if saving finishes before
      ProgressDialog.setVisible(true) is called
      instead of using executor callbacks, use try { } finally { };

    is disposed

commit 5d88441ebe0b874a7d0296c63969686bf457a27e
Merge: de5f869f 3dbeb804
Author: Matthew Horridge <matthew.horridge@stanford.edu>

    Merge pull request #499 from ykazakov/master
    
    Centralize dependencies provided by Protege in bundels

commit 3dbeb804fe42bed10b472965c182337e0d81fb2d
Author: Yevgeny Kazakov <yevgeny.kazakov@uni-ulm.de>
Date:   Thu Aug 4 12:03:24 2016 +0200

    Centralize dependencies provided by Protege in bundels
    
    ... such as guava, owl-api, log4j, etc.
    
    The dependencies that assumed to be provided in the bundels folder are
    moved to protege-launcher, which is included as a dependency with scope
    "provided" in other modules.
    The "provided" scope is used in maven-bundle-plugin to exclude these
    dependencies from the embedded dependencies
    (and hence, not export them in Manifest)
    Previously this was managed manually, which could be error-prone.
    
    All versions of the dependencies (except those for the java runtime
    from the private repository) are now managed in the parent pom.

commit 898c92d1861e5cdfa490e5db307991dacbda3953
Author: Matthew Horridge <matthew.horridge@stanford.edu>
Date:   Mon Aug 8 15:39:04 2016 -0700

    Closes #506 and addresses most of #335
    
    - Added SelectionPlane for marking areas of the UI that have some
    common selection.  This is used by a tab in a workspace to map ui focus
    changes and ui hierarchy changes (e.g. selecting a tab containing a
    navigation driving view) into selection changes.
    - Added the SelectionDriver interface.  Views that can change the
    global selection should implement this interface (out for the box, the
    various hierarchy views and list views do this)

commit 0abea0092efc9360cf33198de7d9abd1d768db70
Author: Matthew Horridge <matthew.horridge@stanford.edu>
Date:   Fri Jul 8 17:40:57 2016 +0100

    Closes #474
    
    This fix actually minimises the applied changes so that redundant axiom
    changes are removed.  Minimisation is applied before changes are
    applied, which means this fix is not specific to the class editor.
    
    Redundant axiom changes include:
    - The addition of an axiom followed by its removal
    - The removal of an axiom followed by its addition
    - The repeated addition of an axiom
    - The repeated removal of an axiom

    Closes #387
    
    If dragging class A from under class B on to owl:Thing in the class
    hierarchy then,
        - SubClassOf(:A :B) is removed.
        - SubClassOf(:A owl:Thing) is not added unless there are
    annotations on SubClassOf(:A :B), in which case the axiom SubClassOf(:A
    owl:Thing) is added with the annotations copied over.

commit dc99d9fdff90755ec7aea985537aa9ac7b3fc8b5
Author: Matthew Horridge <matthew.horridge@stanford.edu>
Date:   Fri Sep 11 11:20:26 2015 -0700

    Packaging changes
    
    - Move config files into a conf directory (Closes #246)
    - Plugins keyed by symbolic id rather than file name. (Closes #244)
    - Added a copy of guava to the bin directory as this is required by the
    launcher module now.  A guava bundle is still contained in the plugins
    directory though.  We need to think of a cleaner way of doing this.
    - Renamed protege-base to protege-launcher (Closes #242)
    - Used resource filtering for setting min/max memory and for the
    location of the logging file. (Closes #247)

commit 6a025cc8968f141e097227f2d0ce05a789497f55
Author: Chris Grieger <chris@scolp.de>
Date:   Wed Jul 8 09:21:57 2015 +0200

    Focus components consistently inside dialogs
    
    Focusing components inside dialogs is not consistent across various
    operating systems and window managers. Overriding the selectInitialValue
    method of JOptionPane should disable the behaviour that automatically
    puts the focus on the OK button of a dialog window.

22	9	org.protege.editor.core.application/src/main/java/org/protege/editor/core/ui/util/JOptionPaneEx.java

    Rename files OWLDescriptionChecker.java  and OWLDescriptionSetChecker.java  to match the classes they contain. This stops maven from recompiling every single java file every single time.
    
    This wasn't getting flagged as an error, because the classes are package local in scope (if they had been public, there would have been  complaints).

commit 883119b805b1b312bb5f5646385f3e1966a79717
Author: Yevgeny Kazakov <yevgeny.kazakov@uni-ulm.de>
Date:   Tue Feb 24 22:58:28 2015 +0100

    Addressing #128
    moved the OWLOntologyChangeListener from
    InferredOWLClassHierarchyProvider to OWLReasonerManagerImpl and issuing
    fireReclassified() in case of logical axiom changes plus import changes
    (which were ignored before). This way all inferences in the UI should be
    updated, not only the inferred class hierarchy.
    Not sure the code was/is safe to guarantee that the reasoner processes
    changes before fireReclassified() because OWLManager processes listeners
    in undefined order. I do not think calling this method within
    SwingUtilities.infokeLater() makes it safe.

commit dcddbf6e815aff1cffd56de414bdd0d7512fd901
Merge: 18756ebe 8cb303ab
Author: Matthew Horridge <matthew.horridge@stanford.edu>
Date:   Fri Feb 20 17:04:26 2015 +0000

    Merge pull request #127 from ykazakov/master
    
    ReasonerProgressUI: fixes and enhancements:

commit 8cb303ab7678e2661ad96451ed13ae8f13463e2a
Author: Yevgeny Kazakov <yevgeny.kazakov@uni-ulm.de>
Date:   Fri Feb 20 16:29:33 2015 +0100

    ReasonerProgressUI: fixes and enhancements:
    1. Making sure that the owner of the progress dialog is not null (moved
    the initialization of the JDialog window from the constructor to a new
    method which runs shortly before the window is accessed)
    2. Centering the window relative to the owner instead of placing in the
    middle of the screen (did not look good with multi-monitor desktops)
    3. Disposing the window on reset instead of making it invisible:
    occationally (especially on linux) some leftovers of the window were
    left after all reasoning tasks complete
    4. All swing-related methods now properly run on AWT thread (including
    updates to the progress bar)
    5. Prevent the progress dialog to close when pressing on the "x" button.
    The user should use the "cancel" button instead
    6. Use a special boolean flag to avoid making the window invisible on
    exit if another reasoner task has already started; in this case, the
    existing window will be reused and only taskLabel updated; this helps
    reducing "flickering" of the progress window in case of many short
    reasoning tasks

106	76	org.protege.editor.owl/src/main/java/org/protege/editor/owl/ui/inference/ReasonerProgressUI.java

commit 18756ebee17605aacbe6547591cdd2d92545264c

commit 65036cd72885a86871db767d858aa993ed961b86
Author: Jennifer Vendetti <vendetti@stanford.edu>
Date:   Thu May 29 11:58:06 2014 -0700

    Don't generate app bundle anymore.
    
    The assembly generates an app bundle that requires Java 6.  This is no
    longer valid as Protege 5.0 beta requires Java 7.  See this issue in
    GitHub for a more detailed discussion:
    https://github.com/protegeproject/protege/issues/29.  When we have time
    to work on generating an app bundle that can use Java 7 or later, we
    could uncomment/modify these lines in the assembler.

4	4	protege-distribution/pom.xml

commit 86f1dcbce67427e66fd42d79e41d6aa733c5c057
Author: Jennifer Vendetti <vendetti@stanford.edu>
Date:   Fri May 9 14:55:37 2014 -0700

    Refactored Maven build file structure.
    
    Used to have a bare bones aggregator at the root, and a parent POM
    at the same level as the submodules. This worked fine until trying to use
    the Maven Release Plugin to perform a release. The release plugin
    wants to include the aggregator in the release process, which doesn't
    make sense for us. Refactored to a slightly simplified approach where
    the POM in the root acts as both the parent and aggregator. The same
    approach is taken by projects like the OWL API.

2	7	org.protege.common/pom.xml
2	7	org.protege.editor.core.application/pom.xml
2	8	org.protege.editor.owl/pom.xml
176	24	pom.xml
2	8	protege-base/pom.xml
2	7	protege-distribution/pom.xml
0	182	protege-parent/pom.xml

commit edc8c760925803c07b043e3e996440e7be00ed44
Author: Jennifer Vendetti <vendetti@stanford.edu>
Date:   Mon Nov 18 17:27:34 2013 -0800

    added error handling for invalid plugin versions
    
    Added code to catch exception when a plugin's update properties file
    contains an invalid version number.  Checking for updates will now
    complete successfully (before, it hung).  Protege logs error in the
    "Protege-Guard", so user can click the red triangle to see exception.
    Exception is also printed to console window, as well as a more human
    readable error message about the invalid version number.  Fixes #18.

commit 32845c490dd39139104fbee21ddc9fe40299b3bf
Author: Jennifer Vendetti <vendetti@stanford.edu>
Date:   Thu Nov 14 12:44:05 2013 -0800

    added new "ide" profile
    
    Created a new profile and moved the lifecycle-mapping,
    maven-dependency-plugin, and maven-clean-plugin to the profile.  Running
    this profile is only necessary if a developer is setting up the Eclipse
    development environment to work with Protege source code (Eclipse PDE +
    m2e +OSGI Framework Launcher mode).  Not desirable to use these plugins
    during a normal command line build.
    
    Upgraded to newer version of maven-bundle-plugin.  Added missing groupID
    for maven-eclipse-plugin.

commit 95e633d7d1f5b25004571f2199ab545fc100e984
Author: Matthew Horridge <matthew.horridge@stanford.edu>
Date:   Sat Feb 4 00:47:47 2012 +0000

    Modified the open/close/save behaviour of Protege.  It now behaves in a more standard way (like MS Word - on Windows).  The welcome screen is no more and Protege now starts with an empty ontology (document).  Opening a new document straight away closes the default empty document.  When all windows have been closed the application exits.
    
    Modified the look and feel.  Icons now resize depending on the size of the font.  Most text in the UI resizes according to the size set in the preferences.

commit a3c8de38ef332984fa8ca07b295fc3f88969490d
Author: Timothy Redmond <tredmond@stanford.edu>
Date:   Thu Oct 13 16:46:34 2011 +0000

    Bug and fix provided by Thomas Hilpold.  Under certain circumstances the roots of the annotation properties were being incorrectly recalculated.  Here is his description:
    
    It occurs like this:
    
    1)      add a new sub property “TestProperty” to any builtin annotation property.
    
    2)      press strg-z undo or delete it using the button
    
    3)      Expected:  “TestProperty” to be deleted, but the builtin annotation property to remain.
    
    4)      Actual: “TestProperty” and the builtin annotation property disappear.

    did not listen for events - either from the model mabnager or events
    that represent changes to the ontology. It turns out that even in the

Author: Timothy Redmond <tredmond@stanford.edu>
Date:   Sun Jan 23 12:04:17 2011 +0000

    The object property selector panel should call the status changed listener even if the validity of the input still appears the same based on internal knowledge.
    
    GForge 2144.   Certain FrameList editors allowed axioms that showed no objects and were not allowed by the specification.  An example was the disjoint classes axiom that would create an all disjoint classes axiom saying that a class was disjoint from nothing else.
    
    To test this we need to check 16 cases:
    
    (Equivalent and Disjoint) x (Classes, Object Properties, DataProperties)
    Same and Different Individuals
    
                   x FrameSection/FrameSectionRow.

commit 8f4527e4c85b3fdd55f76698452faf07b3e42476
Author: Timothy Redmond <tredmond@stanford.edu>
Date:   Tue Oct 19 19:36:48 2010 +0000

    when merging ontologies the merged ontologies should not appear in the imports list.
    
    Jie Zheng mentioned this on the Protege 4 mailing list:
    
    I am working on the Ontology for Biomedical Investigation (OBI). It imported some terms from other OBO foundry ontologies and kept them in the separate owl files. In obi.owl we imported these owl files using <owl:imports rdf:resource="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/obi/external.owl"/>, etc. I used Protege 4.1 (OBI friendly version) to merge these owl files (obi.owl, external.owl ...). Everything worked fine except the import statements still showed up in the merged owl file. Manually removed these import statements did not break anything.
    
    I am wondering whether there is any reason that Protege kept those import statements after merged the imported owl files or it is a bug.
